00:19:53.140 --> 00:20:04.780
But then the prompt to work in a group simultaneously going through those lessons and try to recreate

00:20:04.780 --> 00:20:11.780
something and then go beyond the initial target and say, you have to do something else, but

00:20:11.780 --> 00:20:15.739
it's up to you exactly what that is.

00:20:15.739 --> 00:20:18.660
And then talk about what you did and what you found out.

00:20:18.660 --> 00:20:26.020
That was really valuable to me and I haven't encountered that in a lot of the types of

00:20:26.020 --> 00:20:29.680
classes that I had encountered in the past.

00:20:29.680 --> 00:20:35.900
Maybe that's more common, like I said, I'm not trained as a computer scientist or whatever.

00:20:35.900 --> 00:20:40.459
So there's a lot of different styles of classes out there.

00:20:40.459 --> 00:20:46.979
But the fact that you get something where it's not even like there's multiple correct

00:20:46.979 --> 00:20:53.180
answers, there's an infinite number of correct questions to even try to answer was really

00:20:53.180 --> 00:20:57.420
valuable in my perspective.

00:20:57.420 --> 00:21:00.099
It was a format that worked well for me.

00:21:00.099 --> 00:21:04.540
I can't say that it works well for everybody, but it certainly worked well for me and a

00:21:04.540 --> 00:21:07.540
lot of other people around here.

00:21:07.540 --> 00:21:08.540
Thank you.

00:21:08.540 --> 00:21:09.619
I love that.

00:21:09.619 --> 00:21:14.540
And I love to see how many educators there are in the chat as well.

00:21:14.619 --> 00:21:20.939
Michael, something that was really powerful to me in one of our prep calls is when we

00:21:20.939 --> 00:21:23.459
were talking around career advice.

00:21:23.459 --> 00:21:26.540
And I thought it'd be good to ask that one a little bit earlier today.

00:21:26.540 --> 00:21:31.140
And I was wondering, could you share a piece of career advice that's been meaningful for

00:21:31.140 --> 00:21:36.540
you, whether it's something you've received that you've given others?

00:21:36.540 --> 00:21:38.339
Sure.

00:21:38.339 --> 00:21:46.819
So when people ask me about career advice, the first thing I'll say is I don't really

00:21:46.819 --> 00:21:52.900
know how to advise somebody to end up in a role like mine because I wasn't trying to

00:21:52.900 --> 00:21:57.060
get into a role like mine and it didn't really exist at the time.

00:21:57.060 --> 00:22:03.140
But what I did do is that I kept track of things that I enjoy doing.

00:22:03.140 --> 00:22:10.099
And if you can find a match between things that you enjoy doing and are good at and things

00:22:10.099 --> 00:22:15.260
that other people find valuable but have no interest in doing, you're probably in a really

00:22:15.260 --> 00:22:16.780
good spot.

00:22:16.780 --> 00:22:21.579
So I enjoy a lot of this data manipulation type stuff.

00:22:21.579 --> 00:22:27.300
I enjoy putting together complicated graphics and so forth.

00:22:27.300 --> 00:22:34.219
There's a lot of people who really want absolutely nothing to do with some sort of computer-related

00:22:34.219 --> 00:22:41.640
programming tools and would find it extremely tedious to try to put together a database

00:22:41.640 --> 00:22:52.660
of information or working through all the bugs of the formatting of text or even a graphic

00:22:52.819 --> 00:22:58.020
or designing the table that makes the graphic and all that sort of stuff.

00:22:58.020 --> 00:23:03.500
And a lot of people would find that extremely tedious and not so interesting.

00:23:03.500 --> 00:23:09.619
But I felt a lot of pull from people who wanted the finished product, wanted the finished

00:23:09.619 --> 00:23:16.420
system where they could search through information or make a clean graphic or whatever it is,

00:23:16.420 --> 00:23:21.060
do their lab data analysis more efficiently, whatever it is.

00:23:21.979 --> 00:23:28.219
And I enjoyed the process of making those sorts of tools.

00:23:28.219 --> 00:23:32.900
And so it's worked out well as a nice fit together between those two things.

00:23:32.900 --> 00:23:33.900
Awesome.

00:23:33.900 --> 00:23:34.900
Thank you.

00:23:34.900 --> 00:23:37.900
Curtis, I know you have a question.

00:23:37.900 --> 00:23:42.420
Did you want to hop in here before you have to go?

00:23:42.420 --> 00:23:45.060
I know he's going to drop off at the last hour here.

00:23:45.060 --> 00:23:46.060
Yeah, sure.

00:23:46.060 --> 00:23:49.060
Thanks for letting me cut the line a little bit.

00:23:50.060 --> 00:23:54.780
Michael, you just told a nice story about how just sharing prototype initial work with

00:23:54.780 --> 00:23:59.459
students led to great feedback and puts you on a good path to improve the analytics and

00:23:59.459 --> 00:24:02.140
learning new methods and that sort of thing.

00:24:02.140 --> 00:24:06.060
And then I'm not totally sure I heard this correct, but my understanding of your role

00:24:06.060 --> 00:24:10.819
is you basically collaborate with a ton of different teams and provide them analytic

00:24:10.819 --> 00:24:13.420
services, various services.

00:24:13.420 --> 00:24:18.280
In my experience, that often means there's just often a ton of different collaboration

00:24:18.280 --> 00:24:22.479
styles that you have to work with, which can be a challenge.

00:24:22.479 --> 00:24:27.239
So I actually, on the core question of sharing collaboration, collaboration on the prototype

00:24:27.239 --> 00:24:33.239
stage to maintaining, like oftentimes people build shiny apps that need to be maintained

00:24:33.239 --> 00:24:39.739
for years or regular reports or even just answering questions with a new data set.

00:24:39.739 --> 00:24:44.079
So I was just kind of curious if you had broad tips and tricks, best practices, whatever

00:24:44.079 --> 00:24:48.199
you want to call it for how to have success in that type of environment, which sounds

00:24:48.199 --> 00:24:51.040
pretty challenging to me.

00:24:51.040 --> 00:24:56.959
But also it's like a core way that data scientists can provide tons of value to orgs like Dell.

00:24:56.959 --> 00:24:57.959
Yeah.

00:24:57.959 --> 00:24:58.959
Sure.

00:24:58.959 --> 00:25:07.239
So yeah, there's a lot of different types of questions that you might get asked and

00:25:07.239 --> 00:25:12.719
that will have varying degrees of how easy they are to answer and how easy it is to build

00:25:12.719 --> 00:25:17.079
some sort of shiny app or whatever it is.

00:25:17.079 --> 00:25:23.000
And one of the things that I've learned is it, it really helps if you have the ability

00:25:23.000 --> 00:25:29.400
to sit down with somebody, have them hand you the start of their data, whatever it is.

00:25:29.400 --> 00:25:34.640
And if they can just sketch out a, well, this is what I want it to look like, and maybe

00:25:34.640 --> 00:25:40.599
a little bit of what the math is in between, then you can start putting together a first

00:25:40.599 --> 00:25:42.239
version.

00:25:42.239 --> 00:25:51.719
And if I have a first version, I always like to just hand a shiny app to somebody and say,

00:25:51.719 --> 00:25:54.640
try this, let me watch.

00:25:54.640 --> 00:26:00.479
Because the first thing that they're going to go try to click on tells you a lot about

00:26:00.479 --> 00:26:03.119
what they actually want to be doing.

00:26:03.119 --> 00:26:08.040
So if I hand somebody a webpage and they go, it takes them three tries to click on the

00:26:08.040 --> 00:26:13.920
right thing, okay, I need to either label things differently or design things differently

00:26:13.920 --> 00:26:15.920
or whatever.

00:26:15.920 --> 00:26:22.839
And so just watching the way that somebody interacts with the original data or the tool

00:26:22.839 --> 00:26:28.640
that you've tried to put together goes a very long way.

00:26:28.640 --> 00:26:36.520
And a lot of times it's not too much effort to redesign the display of something.

00:26:36.719 --> 00:26:42.239
It's the calculations and the import and so forth that are the hard part.

00:26:42.239 --> 00:26:47.520
It's the data cleaning and the import and the math that takes more effort.

00:26:47.520 --> 00:26:52.599
And then if you just tweak the display so that your graph switches the axes or switches

00:26:52.599 --> 00:26:59.760
from a bar plot to a scatter plot or whatever it is, that makes life a lot easier and gives

00:26:59.760 --> 00:27:02.319
the real answer that somebody wanted.

00:27:02.319 --> 00:27:10.719
So if you can get a quick prototype out there and let them look at it, that goes a very

00:27:10.719 --> 00:27:11.719
long way.

00:27:11.719 --> 00:27:12.719
I agree.

00:27:12.719 --> 00:27:15.719
Quick wins are important, right?

00:27:15.719 --> 00:27:21.280
Well, I have got a question in the chat from Sonia, but it's got an asterisk next to it,

00:27:21.280 --> 00:27:23.400
so I'm going to ask it.

00:27:23.400 --> 00:27:30.119
And it is, what are some of the helpful or not helpful things that you hear from people

00:27:30.280 --> 00:27:32.239
when they need a project?

00:27:32.239 --> 00:27:35.479
And she said, I know this is a super broad question, but any kind of background information

00:27:35.479 --> 00:27:37.479
would be super helpful.

00:27:37.479 --> 00:27:38.479
Sure.

00:27:38.479 --> 00:27:50.520
So the most helpful thing to me is having a good understanding of what format the underlying

00:27:50.520 --> 00:27:53.520
data actually is part of.

00:27:53.520 --> 00:27:56.800
If somebody says, well, I want to take all this information and I want to put it in a

00:27:56.800 --> 00:28:03.040
more structured database or I want to make a graph out of it or whatever, I want to be

00:28:03.040 --> 00:28:08.640
able to see some of the, like a representative set of the files that everything's sitting

00:28:08.640 --> 00:28:16.359
in right now so that I can tell, okay, how consistent is the naming of your files?

00:28:16.359 --> 00:28:20.640
How consistent is the naming of what's going to end up in a column?

00:28:20.640 --> 00:28:28.119
Is it a bunch of paragraphs of text that have pieces of information in them?

00:28:28.119 --> 00:28:32.520
That's going to take a lot of work if we're actually going to turn that into tables.

00:28:32.520 --> 00:28:41.520
Or maybe it's all sitting in some sort of consistent analytical output that's a spreadsheet

00:28:41.520 --> 00:28:51.239
but is very non-tidy to use programming terminology here.

00:28:51.239 --> 00:28:57.339
If it always comes out the same way, you can probably do something with it.

00:28:57.339 --> 00:29:05.439
And so just that first glance of seeing what the data looks like is huge.

00:29:05.439 --> 00:29:16.479
Some of the non-helpful things, I'm always a person who likes as much information as possible.

00:29:16.479 --> 00:29:25.680
So there's not a lot that's negatively, a negative if they tell me something.

00:29:25.680 --> 00:29:33.280
I will also say that understanding the value in terms of at least how much time it takes for

00:29:33.280 --> 00:29:40.079
somebody to do whatever they're doing right now and how many people would benefit from a new tool.

00:29:40.079 --> 00:29:42.199
That's also huge.

00:29:42.199 --> 00:29:47.959
If you know that the same tool is going to be useful for a couple dozen people, that's

00:29:47.959 --> 00:29:53.239
a lot better than if you're designing it specifically for the one person.

00:29:53.239 --> 00:30:00.959
But if it's one person who spends an hour a day doing the exact same data cleanup or

00:30:00.959 --> 00:30:07.760
whatever it is, it's probably worth it to speed that process up.

00:30:07.760 --> 00:30:16.560
And a lot of times those people will then a few months or years down the line say, oh,

00:30:16.560 --> 00:30:19.439
I have this other idea about something.

00:30:19.439 --> 00:30:26.880
And whether you have time or not, that might be the prompt for them to at least be headed

00:30:26.880 --> 00:30:33.959
towards learning some sort of programming tool or improving the communication with how

00:30:33.959 --> 00:30:36.800
to make a request for some sort of programming tool.

00:30:36.800 --> 00:30:41.119
Because they've thought through the, oh, well, it needs to look like this, and these are

00:30:41.119 --> 00:30:46.880
some of the if-then statements about how I'm going to go about running my calculation.

00:30:46.880 --> 00:30:55.160
I see, well, I just want to say I love seeing how the Dow team supports each other and then

00:30:55.160 --> 00:30:57.719
the community that exists within Dow.

00:30:57.719 --> 00:31:02.040
And I was seeing a few comments from Tony in the chat, and maybe a question.

00:31:02.040 --> 00:31:08.000
So, Tony, I just wanted to ask you if there was a specific question or project that you

00:31:08.000 --> 00:31:12.280
were referring to that you wanted us to chat about, and if you want to ask that to Michael.

00:31:12.280 --> 00:31:16.680
Oh, I dropped like five comments in the chat.

00:31:16.680 --> 00:31:22.000
Yeah, I couldn't keep track of which one, so whichever one is for it.

00:31:22.040 --> 00:31:26.920
I just wanted to mention that Michael actually led a visualization workshop.

00:31:26.920 --> 00:31:29.400
That was one thing, which was really awesome.

00:31:29.400 --> 00:31:32.640
So, he really got into visualization after Academy.

00:31:32.640 --> 00:31:33.479
It was really great.

00:31:33.479 --> 00:31:34.520
I attended it.

00:31:34.520 --> 00:31:39.839
And then the project I wanted Michael to touch on, if anyone wanted to learn, was about his

00:31:39.839 --> 00:31:42.439
breaking down of binary file formats.

00:31:42.439 --> 00:31:49.040
Because it seems like why would you be doing that and why would you use R for that?

00:31:49.040 --> 00:31:53.400
But Michael actually figured out a really great way to do it and made it accessible

00:31:53.400 --> 00:31:54.800
for everyone with a Shiny app.

00:31:54.800 --> 00:32:00.239
And so, you might not think Shiny has a use for breaking down binary file formats, but

00:32:00.239 --> 00:32:01.800
it turns out that is actually not true.

00:32:01.800 --> 00:32:03.000
It's actually pretty good for that.

00:32:03.000 --> 00:32:05.479
So, it's not.

00:32:05.479 --> 00:32:06.959
So, OK.

00:32:06.959 --> 00:32:08.239
So, a couple of things.

00:32:08.239 --> 00:32:12.880
So, on the visualization thing, I will say one of my favorite Shiny apps that I've ever

00:32:12.880 --> 00:32:19.199
put together was something that I used in this visualizations training, which the concept

00:32:19.199 --> 00:32:28.880
there was I liked running a training in the past where, in person, I could just hand out

00:32:28.880 --> 00:32:33.199
a folder to everyone in the room and say, open this in a minute.

00:32:33.199 --> 00:32:39.239
I'm going to put a question up on the board about the things that's in your folder.

00:32:39.239 --> 00:32:40.400
It's got one sheet of paper.

00:32:40.400 --> 00:32:41.839
It's got some data in there.

00:32:41.839 --> 00:32:48.880
Answer this question, I don't know, which catalyst is best at having high conversion

00:32:48.880 --> 00:32:53.280
under these circumstances for the data that's in your folder?

00:32:53.280 --> 00:32:56.439
And just raise your hand when you know the answer.

00:32:56.439 --> 00:33:01.719
And what I didn't tell them is that there were about a dozen different possibilities.

00:33:01.719 --> 00:33:03.020
Some people got bar graphs.

00:33:03.020 --> 00:33:04.359
Some people got scatter plots.

00:33:04.359 --> 00:33:05.599
Some people got a table.

00:33:05.599 --> 00:33:08.640
Some people got whatever.

00:33:08.640 --> 00:33:14.319
And so, some people would just raise their hand in five seconds because they got an immediate

00:33:14.319 --> 00:33:17.520
answer from their scatter plot or something.

00:33:17.520 --> 00:33:29.079
Some people would still be staring at their text 30 seconds later going, why do I feel

00:33:29.079 --> 00:33:30.079
dumb?

00:33:30.079 --> 00:33:33.079
Everyone else is raising their hand and I can't answer this question.

00:33:33.079 --> 00:33:34.079
What am I missing?

00:33:34.079 --> 00:33:45.079
And so, you just got unlucky with a data format that wasn't optimized for this situation.

00:33:45.079 --> 00:33:48.239
And so, I put together a shiny app that does the same thing.

00:33:48.239 --> 00:33:49.239
It's just a web link.

00:33:49.239 --> 00:33:53.760
You click on the link and it's got a random number generated in the background that says

00:33:53.760 --> 00:34:00.239
which of these dozen possible data displays is going to load when you load the page.

00:34:00.239 --> 00:34:06.000
And so, I could run some of these visualization trainings online now or just drop a link in

00:34:06.000 --> 00:34:12.959
the chat and it looks very unsuspicious for everybody to be clicking on the same link.

00:34:12.959 --> 00:34:15.959
I know that they're clicking on the same link.

00:34:15.959 --> 00:34:18.000
That was a lot of fun.

00:34:18.000 --> 00:34:29.120
In terms of the binary file stuff, so a lot of different analytical instruments have their

00:34:29.120 --> 00:34:35.679
own system of how things get categorized or get saved.

00:34:35.679 --> 00:34:41.199
And there's a lot of stuff out there where a particular file format is just a wrapper

00:34:41.199 --> 00:34:42.840
around some other file format.

00:34:42.840 --> 00:34:46.919
So, a .xlsx file is actually a zip file.

00:34:46.919 --> 00:34:53.199
You can change it to a .zip manually on your computer and unzip the thing and find a bunch

00:34:53.199 --> 00:35:00.360
of XML pages and stuff in there, which is always fun to find the pages and the graphics

00:35:00.360 --> 00:35:05.040
and so forth in all these Microsoft file formats.

00:35:05.040 --> 00:35:11.239
And there's a handful of file formats out there that we use regularly that we wanted

00:35:11.239 --> 00:35:14.959
to dig into.

00:35:14.959 --> 00:35:21.439
A lot of those actually have information online where somebody has already published a parser,

00:35:21.439 --> 00:35:25.479
at least to some extent.

00:35:25.479 --> 00:35:31.040
And sometimes it's even a public domain file format where they've described all that information.

00:35:31.040 --> 00:35:35.919
But if somebody has just published a parser online, it's not always complete.

00:35:35.919 --> 00:35:39.679
Maybe there were some things that they missed when they were putting things together.

00:35:39.679 --> 00:35:46.479
And so, the ability to dig around in there has been useful in, well, it's nice to start

00:35:46.479 --> 00:35:51.639
with Excel files if you have those or CSVs or whatever else.

00:35:51.639 --> 00:35:59.000
But sometimes you can't do that and it's helpful to make some tweaks to other file formats

00:35:59.000 --> 00:36:02.439
coming in, which are structured, which goes a long way.

00:36:02.439 --> 00:36:03.439
Thank you.

00:36:03.439 --> 00:36:11.520
Brooks, I see you had a question in the chat and you mentioned some of the work that you're

00:36:11.520 --> 00:36:12.520
doing.

00:36:12.520 --> 00:36:15.520
So, that'd be great to have you jump in and ask that.

00:36:15.560 --> 00:36:16.560
Okay.

00:36:16.560 --> 00:36:22.000
There's an answer already from Tony that might have gotten us to it, but I asked whether

00:36:22.000 --> 00:36:28.719
your dashboards or Shiny apps are mostly for internal use, whether you've had to grapple

00:36:28.719 --> 00:36:36.479
with the challenges of convincing people up above to let you use something external facing

00:36:36.479 --> 00:36:38.879
when they want you to stay in.

00:36:38.879 --> 00:36:42.959
For example, I don't know what it's like for you, but they really want us to stay in the

00:36:42.959 --> 00:36:47.239
Microsoft ecosystem because that's the way they get about security and they're like,

00:36:47.239 --> 00:36:49.600
well, you can do that in Power BI.

00:36:49.600 --> 00:36:55.919
So, I have resistance where I work and I haven't worked here very long, so I don't have a lot

00:36:55.919 --> 00:36:58.959
of credibility for pushing against that resistance.

00:36:58.959 --> 00:37:02.159
Yes, that's a great question.

00:37:02.159 --> 00:37:05.840
It has been much easier for me because I'm making things that are for internal use so

00:37:05.840 --> 00:37:10.600
far.

00:37:10.600 --> 00:37:21.479
We have a sizable organization that is in charge of our DAO.com site and everything

00:37:21.479 --> 00:37:27.000
gets more complicated if it needs to be external facing because we have all this branding that's

00:37:27.000 --> 00:37:34.879
very important to a company like ours to make sure that it's got the right formatting and

00:37:34.879 --> 00:37:39.360
the right color scheme and so forth to fit with everything else DAO.

00:37:39.760 --> 00:37:47.679
When you're just putting together a smaller type of tool for something internal, you don't

00:37:47.679 --> 00:37:50.479
have to worry about that to the same extent, which is nice.

00:37:50.479 --> 00:37:55.600
Now, on the other side, though, I will say we have a number of things that we're working

00:37:55.600 --> 00:38:04.800
on pushing towards external facing tools and the ability to put together a Shiny app or

00:38:04.800 --> 00:38:10.399
a Dash app or a Stringlet app or whatever it may be and say, this is what I want it

00:38:10.399 --> 00:38:11.040
to look like.

00:38:11.040 --> 00:38:17.919
This is the functionality I want, et cetera, I think is really valuable to somebody who's

00:38:17.919 --> 00:38:25.120
more working on the true web interface for the company to say, okay, well, maybe I'm

00:38:25.120 --> 00:38:32.879
going to write that in a different suite of tools, but I can visibly see all the functionality

00:38:32.959 --> 00:38:43.760
that I want to incorporate and that the people using it find important and I think that speeds

00:38:43.760 --> 00:38:52.159
up the process and requires fewer iterations of the back and forth with, hey, here's all

00:38:52.159 --> 00:38:53.120
of our requirements.

00:38:53.120 --> 00:38:56.560
Oh, shoot, we forgot this requirement because we thought it was obvious.

00:38:56.560 --> 00:38:58.080
Now, can you incorporate that?

00:38:59.040 --> 00:39:04.239
Having a prototype, even if it's an internal prototype, goes a very long way on that sort

00:39:04.239 --> 00:39:05.040
of communication.

00:39:06.959 --> 00:39:07.280
Cool.

00:39:07.280 --> 00:39:07.840
Thanks a lot.

