But Lindsay asked-

00:39:36.080 --> 00:39:37.120
I do not have, by the way.

00:39:38.239 --> 00:39:39.679
Well, yeah, that's a great point.

00:39:39.679 --> 00:39:41.280
Michael, what are your degrees in?

00:39:42.080 --> 00:39:43.919
I have a bachelor's in chemical engineering.

00:39:44.959 --> 00:39:45.919
Okay, yeah.

00:39:45.919 --> 00:39:51.679
And a concentration, which is like a minor in material science, but no grad school and

00:39:51.679 --> 00:39:54.239
no formal data science-related degrees for me.

00:39:54.959 --> 00:39:56.479
Yep, and yet here you are.

00:39:56.479 --> 00:40:00.639
Sometimes if you stay open to stuff, you go in that direction.

00:40:00.639 --> 00:40:04.320
Well, we had a question earlier from Lindsay, and it's got an asterisk, so I'm going to

00:40:04.320 --> 00:40:04.879
ask it.

00:40:04.879 --> 00:40:10.399
And it's, how would you quantify the value that learning R has brought to your work?

00:40:10.399 --> 00:40:13.439
And I'm guessing quantify is like hours saved or-

00:40:14.399 --> 00:40:21.840
Yeah, quantifying value of any sort of digital tool has been a major struggle for all of

00:40:21.840 --> 00:40:28.080
us because a lot of times it's in time saved doing a task.

00:40:28.800 --> 00:40:33.120
And then the real question is, would you have even bothered to spend that time doing that

00:40:33.120 --> 00:40:35.520
task if you didn't have the programming tool?

00:40:36.159 --> 00:40:46.000
So one of the biggest compliments, I think, that I can give R is that I had built, like

00:40:46.000 --> 00:40:52.479
run a number of calculations that we just wouldn't have attempted if I didn't have a

00:40:52.479 --> 00:40:53.520
programming tool.

00:40:53.520 --> 00:40:57.520
And so like I can answer questions that we just would have said, we can't do that.

00:40:59.679 --> 00:41:03.600
Now, what number of value can I put on those?

00:41:03.600 --> 00:41:04.560
That's really hard.

00:41:04.560 --> 00:41:10.239
And in terms of time saved on something that also gets messy when you're communicating

00:41:10.239 --> 00:41:17.199
to stakeholders, if you say, well, I saved so-and-so, I saved this group of whatever,

00:41:17.919 --> 00:41:20.800
a dozen people, two hours a week each.

00:41:20.800 --> 00:41:22.560
And they say, oh, that's great.

00:41:22.560 --> 00:41:25.360
Does that mean that we can have one fewer person in our group?

00:41:25.360 --> 00:41:28.320
Well, that's not really the answer that I'm looking for.

00:41:29.760 --> 00:41:33.760
So communication around value there is always a challenge.

00:41:33.919 --> 00:41:43.199
But if you can save some of the tedious steps and answer, that's a good thing.

00:41:43.199 --> 00:41:47.199
If you can answer questions that you just would not have been able to answer in the

00:41:47.199 --> 00:41:52.080
past, because you would have given up first, that's even more value.

00:41:52.080 --> 00:41:58.080
But putting a number on it is not something that I've found a good solution to.

00:42:01.199 --> 00:42:01.760
Thank you.

00:42:01.919 --> 00:42:02.479
Thank you.

00:42:02.479 --> 00:42:03.360
That's really valuable.

00:42:04.399 --> 00:42:09.760
Roberto asked a question a bit earlier with a little star next to it, so I'll read it.

00:42:09.760 --> 00:42:15.040
But it was, how did you overcome the imposter syndrome whenever you couldn't figure out

00:42:15.040 --> 00:42:16.879
how to code or solve something?

00:42:17.439 --> 00:42:21.840
I feel like it's a shared feeling for anyone who learns a new programming language.

00:42:23.439 --> 00:42:23.939
Yeah.

00:42:24.800 --> 00:42:30.000
So fortunately, I was definitely not the first person learning R at Dow.

00:42:30.080 --> 00:42:36.879
And there were some other people like Tony and James, I know is here, and others who

00:42:36.879 --> 00:42:40.239
are very friendly and open to consult on things.

00:42:40.959 --> 00:42:47.120
And one of the things that I think all of us have learned is that if you've got a group

00:42:47.120 --> 00:42:55.280
of people who are all working in the same space, if you've got a new person who asks

00:42:56.239 --> 00:43:02.320
a question, a more experienced person might be able to answer that question, but might

00:43:02.320 --> 00:43:06.399
not have necessarily known that answer directly.

00:43:06.399 --> 00:43:09.439
It's like, I'm 90% sure that the answer is this.

00:43:10.479 --> 00:43:11.040
Let's try it.

00:43:11.040 --> 00:43:11.919
Yep, it worked.

00:43:12.879 --> 00:43:13.439
That's cool.

00:43:13.439 --> 00:43:14.959
I had never thought about it that way.

00:43:15.600 --> 00:43:22.399
So I've learned a ton of stuff from the other broader Dow community in this area.

00:43:22.959 --> 00:43:27.679
But I think I've been able to share quite a few things that they've learned from me

00:43:27.679 --> 00:43:32.159
as well, because I'm asking slightly different questions than they had asked in the past.

00:43:32.879 --> 00:43:42.000
So once you start to realize, like if you have more experienced people who are very

00:43:42.000 --> 00:43:48.879
willing to say, I think it's this, but I've never tried it before, that quickly gets you

00:43:48.879 --> 00:43:54.080
out of the imposter area, because you know that this is not a stupid question.

00:43:54.080 --> 00:43:59.760
I'm doing something that's kind of new and unusual, and that happens very quickly.

00:44:01.520 --> 00:44:08.000
The other thing that I've encountered is that there's a huge amount of information

00:44:08.000 --> 00:44:12.000
online for all these programming languages where you can ask a question in some way,

00:44:12.000 --> 00:44:13.679
and it might give you an answer.

00:44:14.399 --> 00:44:18.560
That goes a long way.

00:44:19.679 --> 00:44:27.760
Convincing people that they're going to get somewhere by Googling it is huge.

00:44:27.760 --> 00:44:34.479
So with one of the recent Posit Academy groups that I was working with,

00:44:36.719 --> 00:44:41.520
one of my favorite moments in that was somebody had a question where they wanted to make a plot

00:44:41.520 --> 00:44:49.040
on a log scale instead of a linear scale, and I said, I want you to share your screen.

00:44:49.040 --> 00:44:50.000
We're all here.

00:44:50.000 --> 00:44:51.679
We've got five minutes left in class.

00:44:52.320 --> 00:44:59.520
I want you to just type something in your search engine in the terminology that you

00:44:59.520 --> 00:45:04.479
would use for figuring this out, and open up a page and see if it gives you the right

00:45:04.479 --> 00:45:07.280
command or the right function to use here.

00:45:08.959 --> 00:45:09.760
Let's go.

00:45:09.760 --> 00:45:10.399
Let's try it.

00:45:11.040 --> 00:45:20.639
And she Googled something, and she found a ggplot function of scale x log or logarithmic

00:45:20.639 --> 00:45:24.800
or something like that that accomplished what she wanted to do, and it was there.

00:45:26.239 --> 00:45:28.159
It was new to everybody in the group.

00:45:28.719 --> 00:45:32.560
I had seen it, but it was new to everyone in the group, and it was, I'm going to make

00:45:32.560 --> 00:45:36.639
you Google this, and you're going to find it, and you're going to get that answer.

00:45:36.719 --> 00:45:44.399
And the confidence that you can do that, and even if it breaks, it wasted 30 seconds of

00:45:44.399 --> 00:45:45.679
it crashing once.

00:45:46.239 --> 00:45:49.040
I can go Google this again, try something else.

00:45:50.000 --> 00:45:51.679
That goes a very long way as well.

00:45:53.199 --> 00:46:01.600
It's a lot easier to run tests on code, especially if you're just doing something like modifying

00:46:01.600 --> 00:46:07.919
the graph, than it is to run a new reaction in lab that may take you hours or days or

00:46:07.919 --> 00:46:08.800
whatever it is.

00:46:08.800 --> 00:46:17.600
And the difference in time there is something that takes a lot of scientists some practice

00:46:17.600 --> 00:46:18.719
to get used to.

00:46:21.199 --> 00:46:22.000
Definitely.

00:46:22.000 --> 00:46:26.959
And on this topic of training and working with other people, I know there's so many

00:46:26.959 --> 00:46:32.080
different community initiatives at Dow, and we've had your team on before to talk about

00:46:32.080 --> 00:46:36.320
those, so I want to make sure I share the link to that Hangout recording as well.

00:46:37.760 --> 00:46:38.959
But a real quick question.

00:46:39.679 --> 00:46:45.360
Bill had asked, where is your physical or virtual physical location, and are you in

00:46:45.360 --> 00:46:47.280
touch day to day with Bench Scientists?

00:46:48.719 --> 00:46:49.439
So, yes.

00:46:50.000 --> 00:46:52.479
I sit in Midland, Michigan, which is the headquarters of Dow.

00:46:53.439 --> 00:47:01.040
And I'm still located in a building that's full of experimentalists, lots of lab space

00:47:01.040 --> 00:47:02.239
and stuff in this building.

00:47:03.360 --> 00:47:13.360
Now, most of my meetings are with people who are not necessarily physically in the same

00:47:13.360 --> 00:47:14.320
building and so forth.

00:47:14.320 --> 00:47:18.560
Some of them are in Midland, some of them are in Texas, some of them are in Pennsylvania,

00:47:18.560 --> 00:47:19.679
some of them are elsewhere.

00:47:20.320 --> 00:47:29.600
And, but I still go to the office and I'm on site more often than not.

00:47:29.600 --> 00:47:34.560
And I find that that sort of in-person interaction of just talking with somebody in the hallway,

00:47:34.560 --> 00:47:39.520
talking to somebody in the break area, the lunch area, whatever, to be extremely valuable

00:47:39.520 --> 00:47:48.479
so that I get the types, the ideas about what frustrations people are running into with

00:47:48.479 --> 00:47:51.280
their own data and the types of things that they might want to answer.

00:47:53.760 --> 00:48:00.320
So, I, a lot of the tasks that I can do, I can do from home, but that sort of personal

00:48:00.320 --> 00:48:03.280
interaction is still really valuable to me.

00:48:04.719 --> 00:48:06.479
I see Alan had asked a question.

00:48:06.479 --> 00:48:10.000
I was just about to call him in, but I think he had to drop for a meeting.

00:48:10.000 --> 00:48:16.879
But he said, given Dow's size, what's the balance between local nimble adoption of tools

00:48:16.959 --> 00:48:22.399
and programs like Academy and the need for broader organization standard-setting

00:48:23.040 --> 00:48:24.000
enterprise support?

00:48:24.560 --> 00:48:28.000
What has made scaling up your program successful in a big org?

00:48:29.040 --> 00:48:33.679
Yeah, it's a hard balance.

00:48:36.959 --> 00:48:39.199
One of the things is that, yes, Dow is huge.

00:48:39.360 --> 00:48:44.800
The R&D data science community within Dow is a lot smaller.

00:48:44.800 --> 00:48:49.280
It's still a lot of people, but it's a much more manageable number of people.

00:48:50.159 --> 00:48:58.159
And so, when you start trying to compartmentalize things that way, it's a lot easier to get

00:48:58.159 --> 00:49:04.479
in touch with the right sets of people from the leadership side of things to say, this

00:49:04.479 --> 00:49:05.439
is what I want to do.

00:49:05.439 --> 00:49:07.280
I think this might be a good way to do it.

00:49:08.239 --> 00:49:09.919
This might be a good way to handle it.

00:49:10.479 --> 00:49:16.639
I think that other people in these other organizations are going to have similar interests.

00:49:17.919 --> 00:49:19.439
What do you think about this?

00:49:19.439 --> 00:49:26.560
And we haven't had a huge number of issues that I've had to deal with on that front.

00:49:28.719 --> 00:49:33.199
There's other people who have been on the administration side of all of our POSIT tools,

00:49:33.199 --> 00:49:40.080
and I think things have gone well there, or at least they've kept me from having to

00:49:40.080 --> 00:49:41.840
worry about it, which is very fortunate.

00:49:43.679 --> 00:49:53.280
Now, like I said, whenever you're crossing functions or crossing spaces that people work

00:49:53.280 --> 00:49:58.159
in, if we want something to go on our external-facing website, then that's different groups

00:49:58.159 --> 00:50:00.239
of people who have to be involved and so forth.

00:50:00.239 --> 00:50:05.439
If we have data sets that are owned by the manufacturing organization instead of the

00:50:05.439 --> 00:50:10.000
research and development organization, that's a different set of permissions to get access

00:50:10.000 --> 00:50:11.280
to all of that data.

00:50:12.000 --> 00:50:20.320
And for the most part, people are understanding if you give them a business case of why you

00:50:20.320 --> 00:50:28.479
need something, at that point, it's a question of how much work is it going to take my organization

00:50:28.479 --> 00:50:29.600
to make that possible?

00:50:30.320 --> 00:50:36.080
How much time is it going to be for us to give you the right permissions to this data?

00:50:36.080 --> 00:50:37.280
Maybe that's fast.

00:50:37.280 --> 00:50:43.439
How much time is it going to be to put this on some site?

00:50:43.439 --> 00:50:44.639
Maybe that's slower.

00:50:45.919 --> 00:50:53.600
Or sometimes you run into security questions as well, as was already asked about, of are

00:50:53.600 --> 00:50:57.600
we okay with somebody in this place having access to this data?

00:50:57.600 --> 00:50:58.719
Maybe yes, maybe no.

00:51:00.479 --> 00:51:07.520
But once you have a clear case of why you're trying to do something, and you can sort of

00:51:07.520 --> 00:51:13.040
narrow down the scope to who's going to care and who's going to have access to it, the

00:51:13.040 --> 00:51:15.919
communication's usually gone pretty smoothly for me.

00:51:18.879 --> 00:51:19.439
Awesome.

00:51:19.439 --> 00:51:20.239
Thank you, Michael.

00:51:20.639 --> 00:51:26.800
I wanted to talk a little bit about success in learning, because I feel like you have

00:51:26.800 --> 00:51:32.080
done really, really well, and it seems like a lot of people at Dow have had a lot of success

00:51:32.080 --> 00:51:37.199
in learning from Academy, or in the communities of learning that you've built internally.

00:51:37.760 --> 00:51:42.000
So I was kind of wondering what the recipe for success is.

00:51:42.000 --> 00:51:46.639
Like, what is it that the managers at Dow are doing to help people have that higher

00:51:46.719 --> 00:51:50.239
probability of success in Academy, or in just learning in general?

00:51:51.760 --> 00:52:00.399
So I think that, in my experience, Dow has always had a good willingness to let people

00:52:00.399 --> 00:52:03.919
learn new skills, and desire for people to learn new skills.

00:52:04.959 --> 00:52:13.679
With Academy itself, I think one of the things that we've learned there is that making sure

00:52:13.760 --> 00:52:20.560
making sure that before somebody even starts going through Academy, that we've been in

00:52:20.560 --> 00:52:27.919
touch with their management chain and got explicit approval that yes, we will set aside

00:52:27.919 --> 00:52:40.479
time for so-and-so to have enough available bandwidth to work on all the lessons and things

00:52:40.479 --> 00:52:43.280
in Academy, that goes a long way.

00:52:43.760 --> 00:52:50.879
And then the other thing is, the faster that you can work with your own data and get some

00:52:50.879 --> 00:52:52.879
benefit out of it, the better.

00:52:53.600 --> 00:52:58.719
So it's more motivating to you, and it's more motivating to your management.

00:52:58.719 --> 00:53:06.479
If three weeks into Academy, you say, I just took this Excel file that I get on a daily

00:53:06.479 --> 00:53:11.280
basis out of some instrument, and I turned it into this graph that I have to make every

00:53:11.280 --> 00:53:14.080
time, and it was faster.

00:53:15.360 --> 00:53:19.600
All of a sudden, you're like, okay, so you set aside this time for me to work on this

00:53:19.600 --> 00:53:23.199
class, and I'm still going to need that time.

00:53:23.199 --> 00:53:27.439
But now one of the other things that I was doing on a daily basis, I don't have to do

00:53:27.439 --> 00:53:27.919
anymore.

00:53:29.919 --> 00:53:34.399
People quickly start to see the value there, and it's exciting for both the leadership

00:53:34.399 --> 00:53:35.520
and the students.

00:53:35.520 --> 00:53:41.919
And that's a really valuable milestone when people hit that.

00:53:42.879 --> 00:53:49.120
So we've had good support, but making sure that we're up front with the communication

00:53:49.120 --> 00:53:55.040
and up front with the approvals and so forth is really important to make sure that people

00:53:55.040 --> 00:54:01.600
don't get pulled away into some other responsibilities of a different training program, into a different

00:54:01.600 --> 00:54:06.000
job responsibility that pops up into whatever.

00:54:06.560 --> 00:54:11.360
We've had people get pulled away into recruiting responsibilities sometimes in the past where

00:54:12.560 --> 00:54:20.639
they're busy with interviews and with talking to candidates and reading resumes and so forth

00:54:20.639 --> 00:54:27.520
where that pops up a couple times a year, but is not a steady thing over the whole year.

00:54:27.520 --> 00:54:34.879
And so all of a sudden, a chunk of their time vanishes that maybe they weren't planning

00:54:34.879 --> 00:54:37.280
to allocate towards academy and camp anymore.

00:54:39.360 --> 00:54:41.919
Michael, did you think an hour could go by so fast?

00:54:43.199 --> 00:54:43.919
It flew through.

00:54:45.199 --> 00:54:51.760
There was a Slido question, which I think is a nice ending question, which is, what's

00:54:51.760 --> 00:54:55.439
the next big thing regarding anything you do with data?

00:54:55.439 --> 00:54:58.000
What are you most excited about for the future?

00:54:59.360 --> 00:55:00.879
Oh, geez, that's a big question.

00:55:10.080 --> 00:55:11.520
That's a hard question as well.

00:55:12.560 --> 00:55:23.679
I think that the next big thing is a lot of times with getting more people aware of what's

00:55:23.679 --> 00:55:29.439
possible with the programming tools, not necessarily teaching them all the programming

00:55:29.439 --> 00:55:36.719
tools, but saying, if people can come in and say, here's this concept that I have, I think

00:55:36.719 --> 00:55:42.959
it might be easy to somebody who knows R or somebody who knows Python or whatever it is,

00:55:43.840 --> 00:55:50.560
and actually being mostly correct on that assessment, even if they don't know the

00:55:50.560 --> 00:55:53.360
programming stuff, that's a huge step forward.

00:55:54.320 --> 00:56:01.199
So trying to put out more broadly useful examples of these things and advertising them to the

00:56:01.199 --> 00:56:06.320
organization and saying, here's a couple examples of something that we've been doing recently,

00:56:06.320 --> 00:56:12.479
you might like some of these, but let us know if you have other ideas of something that

00:56:12.479 --> 00:56:19.439
might fall into the same realm that might look similar, that sort of stuff, come talk

00:56:19.439 --> 00:56:22.239
to us and it might be really fast to accomplish.

00:56:23.679 --> 00:56:29.360
I think that's a big goal for everyone in the data science world, to have the right

00:56:30.159 --> 00:56:37.679
communication with the non-programmers out there who have a lot of great ideas and the

00:56:37.679 --> 00:56:44.000
faster you can filter those down to the ones that are good for computers and the ones that

00:56:44.000 --> 00:56:50.560
are not as friendly for computers to work on, the easier your job becomes.

00:56:54.239 --> 00:57:01.280
Well, thank you so much, Michael, for joining us today and to share your experience.

00:57:01.280 --> 00:57:06.000
And I'm so glad to hear how this experience with Academy has gone for you.

00:57:06.879 --> 00:57:10.719
But just so happy to have so many people from the Dow team here today as well.

00:57:10.719 --> 00:57:16.159
I want to echo what Steve just put into the chat where he said one major factor that has

00:57:16.159 --> 00:57:21.280
driven this movement has also been having the passionate people who consistently advocate

00:57:21.280 --> 00:57:22.399
for these changes.

00:57:23.040 --> 00:57:30.080
So, I've worked with, I know, Tony and James and Camilla and Alex and Amanda, and I just

00:57:30.080 --> 00:57:33.199
really appreciate you and everything that you all do.

00:57:34.080 --> 00:57:35.280
So, thank you so much, Michael.

00:57:36.800 --> 00:57:37.679
Thank you.

00:57:37.679 --> 00:57:41.439
I think there were some questions that I know we didn't get to, and I'm really sorry.

00:57:41.439 --> 00:57:46.320
I'll try and grab those and share them with you, Michael, if that's okay.

00:57:46.320 --> 00:57:47.439
Sure, feel free.

00:57:48.560 --> 00:57:49.040
All right.

00:57:49.040 --> 00:57:50.719
Well, have a great rest of the day, everybody.

00:57:51.280 --> 00:57:52.020
Thank you.

